      <hedline>
        <hl1>Fewer S.U.V.'s Would Aid Environment</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>W Dana Holman letter on May 23 article on water shortages in Westchester, Putnam and Dutchess counties notes area's SUV drivers are polluting air and adding to global warming</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>In the article ''When the Well Runs Dry,'' (May 12), you portrayed the concern of residents of Westchester, Dutchess, and Putnam Counties about their dwindling water supplies. Yet a drive through this area shows that more and more of its citizens are choosing to drive hugely polluting S.U.V.'s. The carbon dioxide from these grossly oversized vehicles contributes significantly to global warming, one of the most likely causes of severe climatic changes like droughts. If Americans continue to buy environmentally destructive automobiles, water shortages will only worsen.W.</p>
        <p>DANA HOLMAN  Manhattan</p>
      </block>
